[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] The acts came into force between 31 December 1800 and 1 January 1801, and the merged Parliament of the United Kingdom had its first meeting on 22 January 1801.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] Provisions of the acts remain in force, with amendments and some Articles repealed, in the United Kingdom, but they have been repealed in their entirety in the Republic of Ireland.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] Two acts were passed in 1800 with the same long title: *An Act for the Union of Great Britain and Ireland*.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] The short title of the act of the British Parliament is **Union with Ireland Act 1800** (39 & 40 Geo.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] 67), assigned by the Short Titles Act 1896.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] The short title of the act of the Irish Parliament is **Act of Union (Ireland) 1800** (40 Geo.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] 38 (I)), assigned by a 1951 act of the Parliament of Northern Ireland, and hence not effective in the Republic of Ireland, where it was referred to by its long title when repealed in 1962.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] Before these acts, Ireland had been in personal union with England since 1542, when the Irish Parliament had passed the Crown of Ireland Act 1542 (33 Hen.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] 1 (I)), proclaiming King Henry VIII of England to be King of Ireland.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] Since the 12th century, the King of England had been technical overlord of the Lordship of Ireland, a papal possession.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] Both the Kingdoms of Ireland and England later came into personal union with that of Scotland upon the Union of the Crowns in 1603.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] In 1707, the Kingdom of England and the Kingdom of Scotland were united into a single kingdom: the Kingdom of Great Britain.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] Upon that union, each House of the Parliament of Ireland passed a congratulatory address to Queen Anne, praying her: "May God put it in your royal heart to add greater strength and lustre to your crown, by a still more comprehensive Union".
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] The Irish Parliament was both before then subject to certain restrictions that made it subordinate to the Parliament of England and after then, to the Parliament of Great Britain; however, Ireland gained effective legislative independence from Great Britain through the Constitution of 1782.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] By this time access to institutional power in Ireland was restricted to a small minority: the Anglo-Irish of the Protestant Ascendancy.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] Frustration among the Catholic majority at the lack of reform, along with other reasons, eventually led to a rebellion in 1798, involving a French invasion of Ireland and the seeking of complete independence from Great Britain.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] This rebellion was crushed with much bloodshed, and the motion for union was motivated at least in part by the belief that the union would alleviate the political rancour that led to the rebellion.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] The rebellion was felt to have been exacerbated as much by reactionary loyalists as by United Irishmen (anti-unionists).
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] Furthermore, Catholic emancipation was being discussed in Great Britain, and fears that a newly enfranchised Catholic majority would drastically change the character of the Irish government and parliament also contributed to a desire from London to merge the Parliaments.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] According to historian James Stafford, an Enlightenment critique of Empire in Ireland laid the intellectual foundations for the Acts of Union.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] He writes that Enlightenment thinkers connected "the exclusion of the Irish Kingdom from free participation in imperial and European trade with the exclusion of its Catholic subjects, under the terms of the penal laws, from the benefits of property and political representation".
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] These critiques were used to justify a parliamentary union between Britain and Ireland.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] Complementary acts were enacted by the Parliament of Great Britain and the Parliament of Ireland.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] The Parliament of Ireland had recently gained a large measure of legislative independence under the Constitution of 1782.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] Many members of the Irish Parliament jealously guarded that autonomy (notably Henry Grattan), and a motion for union was legally rejected in 1799.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] Only Anglicans were permitted to become members of the Parliament of Ireland though the great majority of the Irish population were Roman Catholic, with many Presbyterians in Ulster.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] Under the Roman Catholic Relief Act 1793, Roman Catholics regained the right to vote if they owned or rented property worth £2 annually.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] Wealthy Catholics were strongly in favour of union in the hope for rapid religious emancipation and the right to sit as MPs, which would only come to pass under the Roman Catholic Relief Act 1829 (10 Geo.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] From the perspective of Great Britain's elites, the union was desirable because of the uncertainty that followed the French Revolution of 1789 and the Irish Rebellion of 1798.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] If Ireland adopted Catholic emancipation willingly or not, a Roman Catholic Parliament could break away from Britain and ally with the French, but the same measure within the United Kingdom would exclude that possibility.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] Also, in creating a regency when King George III was rendered unfit to rule by his health issues, the Irish and British Parliaments gave the Prince Regent different powers.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] These considerations led Great Britain to decide to attempt the merger of both kingdoms and Parliaments.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] The final passage of the Act in the Irish House of Commons turned on an about 16% relative majority, garnering 58% of the votes, and similar in the Irish House of Lords, in part per contemporary accounts through bribery with the awarding of peerages and honours to critics to get votes.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] The first attempt had been defeated in the Irish House of Commons by 109 votes to 104, but the second vote in 1800 passed by 158 to 115.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] They were passed on 2 July 1800 and 1 August 1800 respectively, and came into force on 1 January 1801.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] Part of the appeal of the Union for many Irish Catholics was the promise of Catholic emancipation, allowing Roman Catholic MPs, who had not been permitted to sit in the Irish Parliament, to sit in the United Kingdom Parliament.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] This was however blocked by King George III who argued that emancipating Roman Catholics would breach his Coronation Oath, and was not realised until the Roman Catholic Relief Act 1829.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] The traditionally separate Irish Army, which had been funded by the Irish Parliament, was merged into the larger British Army.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] In the first Parliament of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland, the members of the House of Commons were not elected afresh.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] The other 84 Irish parliamentary boroughs were disfranchised; all were pocket boroughs, whose patrons received £15,000 compensation for the loss of what was considered their property.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] The Union Flag, created as a consequence of the union of the Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland in 1800, still remains the flag of the United Kingdom.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] Called the Union Jack, it combined the flags of St George's Cross (which was deemed to include Wales) and the St Andrew's Saltire of Scotland with the St Patrick's Saltire to represent Ireland.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] At the same time, a new Royal Title was adopted ('GEORGE the THIRD by the Grace of God of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland King, Defender of the Faith'), and a new shield of arms.
[src:acts-of-union-1800/acts-of-union-1800] In adopting these, the moribund English claims to the French throne were not continued: the title 'King of France' was abandoned and the fleur-de-lis were removed from the Royal Standard of the United Kingdom for the first time since the Middle Ages.
